<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-162-152 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 696 531</DOCID><JOURNAL>Data Communications  May 1991 v20 n6 p33(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>The secrets of ESF's facilities data link. (extended superframeformat) (WAN Views)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Cotton, Dirk.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>There are many benefits associated with using the extendedsuperframe format (ESF) in data communications on wide areanetworks (WANs).andP;  ESF allows testing of T1 circuits while they arein use, telecommunications interexchange carriers provide ESFservices for free provided users have ESF-compatible equipment andESF provides real-time performance statistics.andP;  In addition, ESFhas an attractive feature called facilities data link (FDL) thatprovides management abilities for a large amount of novel servicesfrom interexchange carriers.andP;  The carriers analyze the statisticscollected by ESF's cyclical redundancy checks and use FDL'stransport mechanism to generate performance reports for customersso they can monitor T1 circuits in their own networks.andP;  ESF alsoenables carriers to identify and pinpoint many problems withoutbeing required to travel to a user's site.andP;  In addition, the FDLtechnology has been integrated in various new applications,including protection switching and network management systems.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Data CommunicationsNetwork ManagementTelecommunicationsStandardizationConnectivityT1 CommunicationsWide Area NetworksCommunications Technology.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andO;Caption:   EFS goes beyond simple framing. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>